    {
      "id": "research-overview",
      "type": "markdown",
      "label": "Graph Theory for Twilite",
      "position": {
        "x": -820,
        "y": 40
      },
      "width": 560,
      "height": 340,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "markdown": "# Graph Theory for Twilite\n## Under a `twilite.zone`-Only Evidence Constraint\n\nThis graph reframes the report as implementation guidance for Twilite.\n\nCore claim:\n- if the graph is the durable artifact, graph theory becomes a correctness model\n- if the assistant \"understands the graph,\" graph semantics and query surfaces must be explicit\n- emerging Twilite concepts like Core Ontology and Node Class Library imply schema, typing, and reusable abstractions already matter\n\nDeliverables in this graph:\n- model choices and assumptions\n- algorithm family selection guidance\n- storage and integration patterns\n- benchmarking design\n- migration and roadmap framing\n",
        "memo": "",
        "link": "",
        "isRoot": true,
        "root": true,
        "_classBinding": {
