    {
      "id": "research-executive-summary",
      "type": "markdown",
      "label": "Executive Summary",
      "position": {
        "x": -160,
        "y": 20
      },
      "width": 540,
      "height": 420,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "markdown": "### Executive Summary\n\nTwilite publicly presents itself as a graph-native persistent workspace where nodes are thoughts, edges are relationships, and AI collaborates against the graph itself.\n\nArchitectural implications:\n- graph theory is not optional math; it becomes part of persistence, merge behavior, querying, and AI grounding\n- graph semantics should be explicit: directedness, multi-edges, typed edges, weights, temporal/versioning, and safe query surfaces\n- Twilite already shows signs of schema and type pressure through public labels like `Core Ontology`, `Node Class Library`, and `Twilite Documentation`\n\nConstraint for this research:\n- only `twilite.zone` may be used as evidence\n- accessible sources establish product intent, but not low-level implementation specifics\n\nSo this graph focuses on:\n- decision frameworks\n- evaluation templates\n- immediate architecture patterns\n- explicit assumptions where internals are not yet published\n",
        "memo": "",
        "link": "",
        "isRoot": false,
        "root": false,
        "_classBinding": {
