    {
      "id": "research-tooling",
      "type": "markdown",
      "label": "Libraries and Tooling Constraints",
      "position": {
        "x": 520,
        "y": 700
      },
      "width": 620,
      "height": 620,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "markdown": "### Libraries and Tooling Under a Platform-Unknown Constraint\n\nWhat matters more than library brand right now:\n- incremental update support\n- predictable memory and latency\n- safe serialization of graph artifacts\n- query expressiveness with agent-safe boundaries\n- maintenance and licensing durability\n\nCross-language evaluation frame:\n- Python tools are useful for prototyping and evaluation harnesses\n- Java and Go are useful for deterministic services and batch compute\n- JavaScript / TypeScript libraries support in-app graph operations\n- Rust becomes interesting if Twilite wants a high-performance portable core, potentially via WASM\n\nThe correct near-term move is not library selection first.\nIt is defining the interfaces and benchmark workloads that any candidate must satisfy.\n",
        "memo": "",
        "link": "",
        "isRoot": false,
        "root": false,
        "_classBinding": {
          "key": "markdown",
          "sourceRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/library/classes/nodes/markdown.node-class.node",
